{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17506091","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17506091"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:40:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:40:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2516"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2516","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2516"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.35,0.16,0.07,0.42,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2516"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78900"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2516","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2516"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2516"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64249"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"404"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2338"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2382"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2793"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8940"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27087"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78900","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78900"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 75-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with pain in her right hip after a fall. She was unable to get up off the floor, and her husband called an ambulance. She is normally in good health, and the only medication she takes is alendronate, together with calcium supplements. On examination, there is limited movement because of the pain, and the right leg appears shortened and externally rotated. X-rays are performed (Image 1, 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate definitive management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Total arthroplasty","Hemiarthroplasty","Single sliding hip screw","Intramedullary nail","Supportive management"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has an extracapsular, subtrochanteric fracture, which is best managed with internal fixation rather than arthroplasty. Specifically, an \u003Cstrong\u003Eintramedullary nail\u003C/strong\u003E is most effective for stabilising this type of fracture, allowing for early mobilisation and weight-bearing. Intramedullary nails provide stable fixation, especially in comminuted fractures, and are preferred for subtrochanteric fractures due to their biomechanical advantages.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETotal arthroplasty\u003C/strong\u003E is typically reserved for intracapsular fractures, particularly in patients with pre-existing joint disease or those who are highly active. It is not the preferred option for extracapsular fractures like subtrochanteric fractures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHemiarthroplasty\u003C/strong\u003E is also generally used for intracapsular fractures, especially in older patients with lower functional demands. It is not suitable for extracapsular fractures, where internal fixation is preferred.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Esingle sliding hip screw\u003C/strong\u003E is another option for extracapsular fractures, particularly intertrochanteric fractures. However, for subtrochanteric fractures, an intramedullary nail is more appropriate due to its ability to handle the biomechanical forces in this region.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESupportive management\u003C/strong\u003E without surgical intervention is not appropriate for this type of fracture in an otherwise healthy elderly patient. Surgical fixation is necessary to allow for mobilisation and to prevent complications associated with prolonged immobility.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Extracapsular fractures are usually managed with intramedullary nail or sliding hip screw.","Intramedullary nails provide stable fixation for subtrochanteric fractures, allowing early mobilisation."],"references":["Callaghan JJ, Liu SS, Haidukewych GJ. Subcapital fractures: a changing paradigm. J Bone Joint Surg Br. 2012 Nov;94(11 Suppl A):19-21. doi: 10.1302/0301-620X.94B11.30617. PMID: 23118374. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23118374/","Bhandari M, Swiontkowski M. Management of Acute Hip Fracture. N Engl J Med. 2017 Nov 23;377(21):2053-2062. doi: 10.1056/NEJMcp1611090. PMID: 29166235. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29166235/","Wong Wei Kang N, Tan WPJ, Phua YMC, Min ATG, Naidu K, Umapathysivam K, Smitham PJ. Intramedullary nail: the past, present and the future - a review exploring where the future may lead us. Orthop Rev (Pavia). 2021 Jul 10;13(2):25546. doi: 10.52965/001c.25546. PMID: 34745479; PMCID: PMC8567815. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34745479/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64249"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2516"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19848"},{"type":"media","id":"19849"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19848","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19848"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e454b7e7-6cb4-496b-99f3-ad657889e349.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e454b7e7-6cb4-496b-99f3-ad657889e349.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":422,"height":600}},{"type":"media","id":"19849","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19849"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8b6397f5-b090-4a83-90f3-e5a25f4390ad